<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-659-939  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 659 939.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Publishing Systems  Nov 26 1990 v20 n6p22(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;ne</JOURNAL><TITLE>New name, direction for Chelgraph LCGS. (Low-Cost Graphics System)(Color and Monochrome Graphics Systems)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chelgraph Ltd. (Management).andO;Topic:     Strategic PlanningComputer Systems IntegratorsTurnkey SystemsPublishing Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>New name, direction for Chelgraph LCGS For Chelgraph, the news was theannouncement of additional features and a change in direction for theLow-Cost Graphics System (LCGS).andP;  The main change is enabling the LCGS to beused with a wider range of products, including PostScript imagesetters.andO;Until now, it has been appropriate really for use only with Chelgraph's Acelanguage and its GIM (Graphics Integration Module) real-time dot-generationscreening module, which is designed mainly to work with Chelgraph RIPs.andM;Because of this change in direction, the LCGS has been renamed the ChelgraphPicture Manager.andP;  The software available for the Picture Manager includes anew scanner control module that is easier to adapt to new scanners and anaccurate on-screen densitometer to allow density readings from the screen.andO;Other enhancements have been made to speed up the system.andM;The main change, however, is support for other graphics editors, rather thanrelying on further development of the graphics editor built into PictureManager.andP;  The first external package to be supported is Astral PicturePublisher.andP;  It also will be able to receive data in TIFF format from othereditors and to export TIFF data.andM;There also will be a standard relational database facility to manage thesystem's large graphics files and links to external wire picture systems.andM;One further development that is not currently available is to be able tooutput data in EPSF format.andP;  This will be released early in 1991.andO;</TEXT></DOC>